<strong>REFERENCE LIST ENTRY</strong>
<br>
<br>
Add a reference list at the end of your essay citing all sources used in the body of your writing.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	Author(s). (Year, Month Day of publication). Title of article. 
	<em>Name of Magazine, volume</em>(issue), page number(s). URL
</blockquote>
<br>
For works without a DOI, if the work was accessed from a website (excluding academic research 
databases, e.g., ProQuest, EBSCO and ScienceDirect) include the URL in the reference. URLs and 
DOIs are displayed as an active link. Works accessed from an academic research database do not 
require a URL or detail about the database in the reference list. In this case, the work would 
be referenced in the same manner as a print version of the work.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	<span class="hover" title="Author(s)">Smith, A., &amp; Brown, B.</span> 
	(<span class="hover" title="Year, Month Day of publication">2017, December 15</span>). 
	<span class="hover" title="Title of article">Chocolate milk could be key to longevity</span>. 
	<em><span class="hover" title="Name of Magazine">New Research International</span>, 
	<span class="hover" title="volume">45</span></em>(5), 
	<span class="hover" title="page number(s)">6&#45;7</span>. 
	<span class="hover fake-aref" title="URL">https://www.times.com/chocolate-milk-could-be-key-to-longevity/story</span>
</blockquote>
