<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
Where a work has two authors always cite both names every time the reference occurs in the text. 
When a work has three or more authors, cite the name of the first author followed by the abbreviation 
et al. (note the full stop after et al.).
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith and Brown (2017) found that&hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: Recent research (Smith &amp; Brown, 2017) supports this view&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once, in the same paragraph, cite the work the first 
time that it is referred to in your writing. Once the work is cited, it is not necessary to 
include the citation again, as long as it is clear that you are referring to the same work 
and that it cannot be confused with other sources being paraphrased. Repeat the citation again, 
if the paraphrase continues into the next paragraph.  
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	In a recent study, Smith and Brown (2017) showed that&hellip; Smith and Brown also found 
	that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are using a direct quotation, consisting of fewer than 40 words, enclose the quote using 
double quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith and Brown (2017) observe that &#34;chocolate has grown in popularity with adolescents&#34; 
	(p. 34).
	<br>
	Alternatively: &#34;Chocolate is growing in popularity with adolescents&#34; (Smith &amp; Brown, 
	2017, p. 34).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 40 words, the quote is displayed in a double spaced, indented 
block at 1.27cm from the left margin. Do not use double quotation marks to enclose a block quotation.
